59
00:04:03,448 --> 00:04:10,732
[SPEAKER_10]: So just to give a little bit more of an introduction on who I am, I know that I haven't got the chance to meet most of you in person.

60
00:04:11,532 --> 00:04:14,514
[SPEAKER_10]: I've been working for the city of Medford for over three years.

61
00:04:15,474 --> 00:04:24,118
[SPEAKER_10]: The first two years in the planning, development and sustainability office where I was very much involved with the first COVID-19 relief efforts.

62
00:04:24,819 --> 00:04:33,023
[SPEAKER_10]: I helped provide administrative support for the COVID-19 rental assistance program and the COVID-19 small business grant relief program.

63
00:04:33,753 --> 00:04:50,565
[SPEAKER_10]: And from there, I moved and was promoted to the procurement office, where I managed and was responsible for executing a variety of bid solicitation and city contracts that included some procurements of ARPA-funded projects and programs.

64
00:04:51,205 --> 00:05:02,513
[SPEAKER_10]: So I'm very glad that this transition has been smooth for me, and I'll be sharing the progress that we've made so far.

65
00:05:05,683 --> 00:05:27,533
[SPEAKER_10]: So the content of this presentation will be sharing the ARPA community survey results, then giving you all the high level summary of the ARPA allocations and approved projects so far, which will then lead to a discussion of future spending plans and how the community input received from the community survey will be incorporated into the ARPA strategy.

66
00:05:31,355 --> 00:05:37,660
[SPEAKER_10]: These are a few data points on the participation rates and the engagement that we received.

67
00:05:38,441 --> 00:05:42,504
[SPEAKER_10]: We received a total of 416 responses from the survey.

68
00:05:42,524 --> 00:05:50,651
[SPEAKER_10]: 95% of respondents live in Medford and 71% of participants work full time.

69
00:05:51,492 --> 00:05:58,718
[SPEAKER_10]: For the complete copy of the community survey results, including the original template and

70
00:05:59,120 --> 00:06:03,362
[SPEAKER_10]: the data received, we'll be posting that on the Medford ARPA webpage.

71
00:06:08,964 --> 00:06:18,888
[SPEAKER_10]: These next section of the community survey results will highlight the community values, the top areas, and needs that were identified by the public.

72
00:06:22,405 --> 00:06:32,734
[SPEAKER_10]: Out of a list of different key areas where ARPA funding should be invested in, these were the top three chosen areas, which were water, sewer, street improvements.

73
00:06:33,855 --> 00:06:37,138
[SPEAKER_10]: Number two, improvements to outdoor green and park spaces.

74
00:06:38,099 --> 00:06:47,428
[SPEAKER_10]: And number three, investment in social services, including but not limited to housing services, food assistance, mental health services, and childcare, et cetera.

75
00:06:50,687 --> 00:07:00,073
[SPEAKER_10]: The top human service needs identified were mental and behavioral services, childcare and youth services, and homelessness prevention.

76
00:07:04,556 --> 00:07:15,983
[SPEAKER_10]: And this slide represents a section in the survey where we asked respondents to select the top nonprofits to be supported with additional ARPA funding.

77
00:07:16,423 --> 00:07:19,005
[SPEAKER_10]: And these are some of the existing partners

78
00:07:19,820 --> 00:07:37,327
[SPEAKER_10]: we have in Medford, which are the Medford Family Network, the Friends of the Fells, the Medford Youth Center at Mystic Valley, YMCA, the ABCD Mystic Valley Housing Services, and the National Alliance on Mental Illness, serving Medford and the greater Middlesex region.

79
00:07:38,608 --> 00:07:46,991
[SPEAKER_10]: And just to connect with the previous slide, these providers address the childcare,

80
00:07:47,582 --> 00:07:59,397
[SPEAKER_10]: a youth programming needs from the previous side, mental and behavioral services, and ABCD supports in a range of housing support programs for Medford.

81
00:08:03,413 --> 00:08:16,782
[SPEAKER_10]: For this last section on the community survey results, I wanted to share with you all some individual responses that we received from the public, where we asked the public to answer the following question.

82
00:08:16,882 --> 00:08:19,844
[SPEAKER_10]: How were you impacted by the pandemic?

83
00:08:20,425 --> 00:08:23,167
[SPEAKER_10]: And these were a few of the many responses that we received.

84
00:08:26,149 --> 00:08:28,190
[SPEAKER_10]: Income, anxiety, childcare needs.

85
00:08:29,471 --> 00:08:31,032
[SPEAKER_10]: Children suffered mentally.

86
00:08:33,105 --> 00:08:35,670
[SPEAKER_10]: Loss of work greatly impacted mental health.

87
00:08:37,734 --> 00:08:39,378
[SPEAKER_10]: Isolation and solitude.

88
00:08:41,542 --> 00:08:43,226
[SPEAKER_10]: Our small business was very hard hit.

89
00:08:46,888 --> 00:08:53,833
[SPEAKER_10]: Before the inception of ARPA, the administration and the board of health have tackled many of these challenges and impacts.

90
00:08:54,814 --> 00:09:15,130
[SPEAKER_10]: During the wake of the pandemic, for example, the board of health department launched many community outreach programs, such as the multilingual resource line to help connect with those in need to our local resources and help the people in need and following up with them throughout the process.

91
00:09:17,432 --> 00:09:22,993
[SPEAKER_10]: The RUOK program to address social isolation and solitude among elders.

92
00:09:23,593 --> 00:09:41,657
[SPEAKER_10]: With ARPA, we've staffed many COVID-19 staff positions, including a community social worker, a health equity and outreach coordinator, and five multilingual community liaisons to help with additional outreach efforts with the Board of Health.

93
00:09:45,538 --> 00:09:48,540
[SPEAKER_10]: And in addition, one of the campaign goals.

94
00:09:49,741 --> 00:10:01,629
[SPEAKER_10]: And what was really at the forefront with the administration was to create an economic development department, even before the pandemic, and the pandemic really accelerated the progress on this.

95
00:10:02,670 --> 00:10:21,523
[SPEAKER_10]: In addition, with ARPA funding, we've expanded the economic development program by hiring two positions, which are an economic development staff planner and an economic development intern to help aid the director with small business support programs and other economic development initiatives.

96
00:10:25,678 --> 00:10:37,227
[SPEAKER_10]: And now we'll move on to the many projects and programs that we've approved and implemented so far that address many of these key areas and needs identified by the public.

97
00:10:42,471 --> 00:10:50,918
[SPEAKER_10]: Medford took on a needs-based approach driven by department heads for projects and initiatives that were emergent.

98
00:10:51,446 --> 00:10:55,708
[SPEAKER_10]: We've expended and allocated across 6 different are eligible.

99
00:10:56,829 --> 00:11:06,314
[SPEAKER_10]: Use categories and this bar graph represents 5 out of those 6 eligible expense categories which are public health in blue.

100
00:11:07,495 --> 00:11:09,316
[SPEAKER_10]: Negative economic impact in green.

101
00:11:10,256 --> 00:11:12,057
[SPEAKER_10]: Public sector workforce in orange.

102
00:11:13,178 --> 00:11:20,342
[SPEAKER_10]: Infrastructure in purple and the are but ministry of expense category which is the pool of funding that I'm

103
00:11:21,005 --> 00:11:21,565
[SPEAKER_10]: paid from.

104
00:11:23,026 --> 00:11:24,287
[SPEAKER_10]: So the top.

105
00:11:25,508 --> 00:11:34,514
[SPEAKER_10]: Largest expenditure category so far have been the negative economic impact category and the infrastructure category.

106
00:11:37,857 --> 00:11:49,525
[SPEAKER_10]: In the following sites are going to each more detail on each category and list out of the projects that we've approved so far starting with the largest expense category.

107
00:11:50,599 --> 00:12:04,084
[SPEAKER_10]: We've approved the renovation of Tufts pool deck, which includes the demolition of the previous deck and installation of a remodel and addition of a water mushroom.

108
00:12:04,824 --> 00:12:15,628
[SPEAKER_10]: The free one month trial memberships of blue bikes to low income residents, which was a joint effort between the city of Malden and the city of Medford under our bike share lift contract.

109
00:12:17,249 --> 00:12:20,911
[SPEAKER_10]: The McGlynn playground redesigned for a university accessible playground.

110
00:12:22,211 --> 00:12:38,840
[SPEAKER_10]: Support for community memorial gardens at Medford High School, which was a very special project that I was a part of when I worked in procurement to commemorate the lives of the mentors and teachers that their lives were lost due to COVID-19 and cancer.

111
00:12:38,860 --> 00:12:42,222
[SPEAKER_10]: The parking meter upgrades in Medford Square.

112
00:12:43,662 --> 00:12:46,864
[SPEAKER_10]: Car park phase two, which includes a four season

113
00:12:47,700 --> 00:13:09,227
[SPEAKER_10]: improvements in addition to water play and a covered basketball court, the Gillis Park Accessibility Renovation Project, and a most recent project between a joint request between the Council on Aging and Recreation, which is a transportation van share program.

114
00:13:10,145 --> 00:13:24,495
[SPEAKER_10]: to address the unmet need of transporting our seniors to medical appointments and grocery shopping and youth to expand recreational activities and provide child care assistance.

115
00:13:28,758 --> 00:13:32,841
[SPEAKER_10]: Our next category, the projects under infrastructure.

116
00:13:32,861 --> 00:13:39,106
[SPEAKER_10]: I want to remind everyone that they're under the final rule must be

117
00:13:39,848 --> 00:13:48,712
[SPEAKER_10]: related to water and sewer or broadband, with just a few exceptions, but for the most part, must be water sewer related.

118
00:13:49,332 --> 00:14:05,620
[SPEAKER_10]: Some of the projects that we've implemented have been the sewer lining upgrades as part of the city's wastewater collection rehabilitation project, the centralized wastewater treatment projects on Main Street and Mystic Avenue,

119
00:14:07,412 --> 00:14:34,465
[SPEAKER_10]: the DPW water meter replacement project for our clean water improvements, flood mitigation assessment, a lead rebate program, which was originally funded in the past years with another source of funding, but that funding source has depleted and we've used ARPA to replenish the program to be able to continue it since it's very well received and successful in Medford.

120
00:14:36,356 --> 00:14:45,778
[SPEAKER_10]: other water upgrades on Pinker Street, the Medford fire safety alerting system, and the fiber optic municipal building upgrade.

121
00:14:50,159 --> 00:14:52,300
[SPEAKER_10]: I'll just quickly go over again this slide.

122
00:14:52,740 --> 00:15:02,102
[SPEAKER_10]: We've staffed many COVID-19 staff positions, and we've also used this pool of funding for translation services and communications related to COVID.

123
00:15:08,009 --> 00:15:12,851
[SPEAKER_10]: And last but not least, the public health emergency category.

124
00:15:13,511 --> 00:15:33,777
[SPEAKER_10]: Although it seems like it's the lowest one, I wanna remind everyone that the prior iteration of COVID-19 funding, which was CARES, a lot of that funding was directed to the Board of Health for administrative support and emergency supplies and equipment to run vaccine clinics and additional support for them as well.

125
00:15:35,945 --> 00:15:40,648
[SPEAKER_10]: With ARPA funding so far, we've funded the following projects.

126
00:15:41,348 --> 00:16:04,622
[SPEAKER_10]: Infection control stations, rapid COVID-19 tests, a multi-language kiosk payment system at the parking department, which will prevent the spread of COVID-19 by preventing congregation in public settings while also increasing accessibility for our multilingual and immigrant communities.

127
00:16:06,330 --> 00:16:32,442
[SPEAKER_10]: the water filling stations installed in our schools, a public health rodent program, voting booth upgrades, voting poll pads for our elections, an emergency and response planning and training contract with the Metropolitan Area Planning Council for future emergency planning for any health crisis in the future, and food inspections government mandate project.

128
00:16:34,892 --> 00:16:48,804
[SPEAKER_10]: So in summary, we've allocated more than half of the total grant funding received, and the remaining total of unallocated grant funding is about 19.7 million.

129
00:16:49,625 --> 00:16:59,813
[SPEAKER_10]: And this portion of the pie in green, I just wanna note that it does not include the revenue replacement budget for fiscal year 24 and fiscal year 25.

130
00:17:05,233 --> 00:17:12,759
[SPEAKER_10]: So with the $19.7 million remaining in ARPA funding, this is an outline of how we plan to spend it.

131
00:17:14,881 --> 00:17:26,130
[SPEAKER_10]: We would like to set aside $3 to $4 million to go towards nonprofit support and affordable housing projects that have been proposed to the mayor and I by the Medford Housing Authority.

132
00:17:26,150 --> 00:17:34,217
[SPEAKER_10]: We will be opening up a grant subrecipient process for nonprofits to be able to apply

133
00:17:34,990 --> 00:17:37,371
[SPEAKER_10]: on Jen in some time in January of 2023.

134
00:17:37,491 --> 00:17:57,280
[SPEAKER_10]: We're also looking to set aside 2 million to be allocated for any department had requests that we received over these past few days and recurring our expenses associated with the staff salaries that are funded through December 31st 2024.

135
00:18:00,421 --> 00:18:04,383
[SPEAKER_10]: And so the remaining large portion of this pie and

136
00:18:05,218 --> 00:18:13,187
[SPEAKER_10]: light blue will be hoping to dedicate it to future water sewer infrastructure projects and revenue replacement.

137
00:18:22,251 --> 00:18:37,795
[SPEAKER_10]: So I think I'm pretty sure everyone knows what revenue replacement is in this room, but just as a reminder, this is the sixth eligible use expense category that gives cities a broad latitude to use funds for the provision of government services.

138
00:18:38,655 --> 00:18:42,476
[SPEAKER_10]: In particular, Medford has used its revenue replacement

139
00:18:43,385 --> 00:18:49,429
[SPEAKER_10]: to transfer in our budgets, our school budgets for fiscal year 22 and fiscal year 23.

140
00:18:50,590 --> 00:19:00,896
[SPEAKER_10]: We've also used it for a Medford high school facility assessment, IT and cybersecurity and for recruitment purposes.

141
00:19:02,137 --> 00:19:08,281
[SPEAKER_10]: But for this, this graph is what shows what we predict our revenue replacement

142
00:19:08,688 --> 00:19:12,989
[SPEAKER_10]: to be for the fiscal year 2024 fiscal year 2025.

143
00:19:13,089 --> 00:19:35,997
[SPEAKER_10]: We expect revenues to rise and therefore there be a decline in the following years for revenue replacement increasing the pool of funding that will be used for nonprofit and affordable housing and those other key eligible expense categories that review we reviewed previously.

144
00:19:41,476 --> 00:19:52,700
[SPEAKER_10]: So we're almost to the end of this presentation, but before I conclude, I'd like to share with you all some creative ways that we've been inspired by other communities and how they've spent their ARPA funding.

145
00:19:53,521 --> 00:20:06,366
[SPEAKER_10]: We hope to emulate the following projects, which are the Chamber of Commerce for yearly memberships and some small business festivals when the weather gets warmer.

146
00:20:07,473 --> 00:20:35,932
[SPEAKER_10]: a range of youth programming, rental assistance and fuel assistance, a language access plan for our translation needs, for our press releases as well, and translation and building signage, a ride share programs, such as the blue bikes that we've undertook, and the van share program for our elders and our youth, and a broad range of facilities upgrades.

147
00:20:39,985 --> 00:20:46,990
[SPEAKER_10]: So to conclude, the community survey results are really a testament of our community values and needs.

148
00:20:47,731 --> 00:20:56,638
[SPEAKER_10]: We'll also factor in project readiness and priorities identified in earlier processes to determine what future projects get approved.

149
00:20:56,658 --> 00:21:01,141
[SPEAKER_10]: And I'd like to thank you all for your time.

150
00:21:01,221 --> 00:21:09,187
[SPEAKER_10]: And it was a pleasure to share the many ways in which Medford has made large strides in recovering from the pandemic fully and equitably.

151
00:21:10,418 --> 00:21:10,758
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

152
00:21:11,939 --> 00:21:12,759
[SPEAKER_11]: Questions from the council?

153
00:21:14,060 --> 00:21:14,620
[SPEAKER_11]: Councilor Carvajal.

154
00:21:15,480 --> 00:21:16,160
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Madam President.

155
00:21:16,521 --> 00:21:22,003
[SPEAKER_01]: So all the projects that you said, they're all worthwhile.

156
00:21:22,043 --> 00:21:23,264
[SPEAKER_01]: They're all worthy projects.

157
00:21:24,364 --> 00:21:30,347
[SPEAKER_01]: My question is, we seem to be devoting a lot of money to water and sewer projects.

158
00:21:31,307 --> 00:21:34,628
[SPEAKER_01]: We have an enterprise with millions of dollars in it.

159
00:21:34,789 --> 00:21:37,670
[SPEAKER_01]: Why are we using ARPA funds when

160
00:21:38,599 --> 00:21:45,162
[SPEAKER_01]: we have money to pay for a lot of these projects already put aside, the water and sewer enterprise accounts.

161
00:21:45,362 --> 00:21:51,545
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, so in fact, our infrastructure project right now is the second largest expense category.

162
00:21:51,925 --> 00:21:56,927
[SPEAKER_10]: Our largest expense category is the negative economic impact category.

163
00:21:57,747 --> 00:22:06,171
[SPEAKER_10]: But to address your question, I'm not a financial advisor on how the city spends funding, but what I know from ARPA is that

164
00:22:07,181 --> 00:22:12,565
[SPEAKER_10]: Water and sewer is an eligible use categories across all communities.

165
00:22:12,645 --> 00:22:21,652
[SPEAKER_10]: And with my research that I've done, a lot of the other communities have used a lot of the ARPA funding for water and sewer.

166
00:22:22,172 --> 00:22:32,280
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm not questioning you, but we have probably about six, $7 million in our water and sewer enterprise account, which is supposed to be used for projects like these.

167
00:22:34,563 --> 00:22:42,168
[SPEAKER_01]: some of this money that we're dedicating to these projects could go to other projects that are probably maybe more, maybe more needing or something like that.

168
00:22:42,208 --> 00:22:51,975
[SPEAKER_10]: That's just- I also think like some of the water sewer projects are directly public health related as they're improvements to clean water, for example.

169
00:22:52,155 --> 00:22:57,338
