370
00:41:09,993 --> 00:41:12,954
[SPEAKER_05]: So thank you so much for all of your work on this survey and doing the outreach.

371
00:41:15,255 --> 00:41:19,937
[SPEAKER_05]: All of my questions that I had written down before this meeting have been asked by my fellow counselors.

372
00:41:20,017 --> 00:41:27,880
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't want to retread over things we've already discussed, but just in the spirit of giving feedback on city projects and knowing that this is not

373
00:41:29,772 --> 00:41:34,936
[SPEAKER_05]: your project to manage, but certainly you're not the only decision maker when it comes to the allocation of our ARPA funding.

374
00:41:34,976 --> 00:41:38,939
[SPEAKER_05]: So this is more comment on the overall scope of work here.

375
00:41:38,979 --> 00:41:42,942
[SPEAKER_05]: And I know that you're just the messenger, whether the news is good, bad, or just interesting.

376
00:41:44,843 --> 00:41:54,331
[SPEAKER_05]: But I did also just want to chime in and note on a couple of aspects of this regarding

377
00:41:55,434 --> 00:41:58,138
[SPEAKER_05]: how the feedback is allocated amongst the city.

378
00:41:58,218 --> 00:42:10,935
[SPEAKER_05]: It's been said before, but I heard from other constituents as well, concern over the racial and economic and living circumstance makeup of those who responded to the survey.

379
00:42:11,215 --> 00:42:11,375
[SPEAKER_05]: Again,

380
00:42:12,136 --> 00:42:13,397
[SPEAKER_05]: that doesn't lie with you.

381
00:42:13,517 --> 00:42:18,380
[SPEAKER_05]: I've made lots of comments before about the city's capacity for robust communication outreach strategy.

382
00:42:18,820 --> 00:42:19,981
[SPEAKER_05]: I think this is a symptom of that.

383
00:42:20,261 --> 00:42:21,302
[SPEAKER_05]: That's a long-term project.

384
00:42:21,362 --> 00:42:34,010
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm glad that there's some language access programs already baked into our allocation of future ARPA spending, and that'll be a great start, I think.

385
00:42:34,090 --> 00:42:36,312
[SPEAKER_05]: Overall, what I want to give voice to is that

386
00:42:36,782 --> 00:42:59,661
[SPEAKER_05]: I've been hearing from residents for months that we want to make sure that this survey and, more importantly, our actual spending patterns, you know, meaningfully incorporate the perspectives of our entire community and also people who are most marginalized in our community, those who are most likely to be hardest hit by the pandemic and, unfortunately, those who are least likely to be reached by the survey and reached by survey communications in general.

387
00:43:00,702 --> 00:43:06,851
[SPEAKER_05]: So again, that's that's not a criticism of anybody in the room but that's just something that I wanted to put on the record.

388
00:43:07,713 --> 00:43:15,564
[SPEAKER_05]: And in addition, we already touched on this a little bit, but I'm really interested in metrics for how that future spending.

389
00:43:16,765 --> 00:43:31,830
[SPEAKER_05]: will be tracked and cataloged and we'll make sure that it does hew to the priorities expressed by the constituency and the surveys, you know, where there's still a little bit of ambiguity in the unallocated, especially since we don't have the budget numbers for the revenue replacement yet.

390
00:43:33,211 --> 00:43:43,454
[SPEAKER_05]: I think as an accountability measure, I'm really interested and this constituency is really interested in saying, you know, like President Murrell touched on, we had this much money available

391
00:43:44,687 --> 00:43:46,428
[SPEAKER_05]: These are the projects that we considered for it.

392
00:43:46,548 --> 00:43:51,149
[SPEAKER_05]: This is how much money we decided on it, and we did it using this algorithm or this rubric.

393
00:43:51,789 --> 00:43:58,272
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that'll be really important for the community to really be able to see this is how my input was incorporated.

394
00:43:59,592 --> 00:44:00,872
[SPEAKER_05]: So thank you again for all your work.

395
00:44:01,533 --> 00:44:02,073
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

396
