410
00:45:03,443 --> 00:45:05,224
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you so much for being here for the presentation.

411
00:45:09,366 --> 00:45:11,388
[SPEAKER_11]: Moving to 22-014, this paper is on the potential opt-in

412
00:45:15,583 --> 00:45:19,547
[SPEAKER_11]: for paid family medical leave for municipal employees for the city of Medford.

413
00:45:19,587 --> 00:45:22,130
[SPEAKER_11]: We met on this all the way back in February.

414
00:45:22,430 --> 00:45:28,536
[SPEAKER_11]: And there was a motion for a few upcoming meetings on this, eventually to talk to union leaders.

415
00:45:29,077 --> 00:45:34,622
[SPEAKER_11]: But one of the main things that we were hinging on is the potential financial impact of the city opting into this.

416
00:45:34,722 --> 00:45:37,405
[SPEAKER_11]: So finally having our finance director here with us.

417
00:45:38,273 --> 00:45:59,920
[SPEAKER_11]: Hopefully we can address some of the questions and continue the conversations as the council, I believe the majority, if not all of the council expressed an interest in this, but of course there are questions on what the financial impact would be to opt city employees into this extended leave program that most private companies are already opted into.

418
00:46:01,561 --> 00:46:06,743
[SPEAKER_11]: Would anyone like to start with questions or finance director Dickinson, is there any,

419
00:46:09,450 --> 00:46:11,031
[SPEAKER_11]: to share with us or anything related to this?

420
00:46:12,051 --> 00:46:19,353
[SPEAKER_11]: I do not believe in the time period since we first started talking about this that any other municipalities have opted in.

421
00:46:19,973 --> 00:46:22,654
[SPEAKER_11]: Okay.

422
00:46:23,414 --> 00:46:25,155
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, madam president.

423
00:46:26,715 --> 00:46:30,976
[SPEAKER_08]: So I think you heartfully said this is a council priority.

424
00:46:31,036 --> 00:46:35,157
[SPEAKER_08]: We really are very supportive of this initiative.

425
00:46:35,698 --> 00:46:36,418
[SPEAKER_08]: We think it shows

426
00:46:37,440 --> 00:46:45,103
[SPEAKER_08]: real opportunity not just to support all of the people who work for the city and the school department, but an opportunity for Medford to lead.

427
00:46:46,143 --> 00:47:00,748
[SPEAKER_08]: As you noted in 2018, the paid family medical leave law was passed and offered to every worker in Massachusetts except public employees, particularly municipal employees.

428
00:47:01,929 --> 00:47:02,109
[SPEAKER_08]: So

429
00:47:03,171 --> 00:47:27,538
[SPEAKER_08]: when we talk about recruitment and retention and the difficulties with bringing folks to the city, one of the potential issues with that competition is that if you wanna say work in an engineering job or a communications job or a clerical job, you may have a better benefits package working in private industry than in the city of Medford.

430
00:47:29,207 --> 00:47:48,537
[SPEAKER_08]: And, you know, there's also by joining a large pool, which is essentially what the state's paid family medical leave insurance is, we benefit by being part of, you know, a larger insurance pool, which can means that the, you know, we're benefiting from sharing the costs and the burden of that.

431
00:47:50,267 --> 00:48:00,612
[SPEAKER_08]: And I'll just finally note that the authority within the law for a municipality to join this program sits with the legislative body, in this case, the city council.

432
00:48:00,732 --> 00:48:03,713
[SPEAKER_08]: So those are just some of the reasons that I think this is important.

433
00:48:03,853 --> 00:48:06,874
[SPEAKER_08]: It was one of our top priorities, one of the first things we introduced in January.

434
00:48:07,494 --> 00:48:12,857
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm glad we are at a point where we can meet with Director Dickinson about what the impact of this might be.

435
00:48:14,257 --> 00:48:14,878
[SPEAKER_08]: But again, it's,

436
00:48:16,273 --> 00:48:19,934
[SPEAKER_08]: There's about a million reasons why this is a good idea.

437
00:48:20,214 --> 00:48:20,534
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

438
00:48:20,914 --> 00:48:32,598
[SPEAKER_11]: And just first is embarrassed to add on to that we did ask former city solicitor, Kim Scanlon, as far as the, just the vote required for this and it would just be a civil majority to vote for this.

