[SPEAKER_09]: Then I put 2024, I just given, hopefully, a nice 2% COLA for people plus contractual obligations with step increases, et cetera.

514
00:56:33,667 --> 00:56:38,992
[SPEAKER_09]: I just added 1.025 to the 637 to see what it might look like for 2024.

515
00:56:39,052 --> 00:56:40,753
[SPEAKER_09]: Obviously, that can change.

516
00:56:45,564 --> 00:56:50,465
[SPEAKER_09]: Just so you know, the 2023 rates for this are actually lower than they were for 2022.

517
00:56:52,245 --> 00:56:55,446
[SPEAKER_09]: So they could change in the future.

518
00:56:55,726 --> 00:56:57,706
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't know if they'll go up or if they'll go down.

519
00:56:58,546 --> 00:57:00,106
[SPEAKER_09]: That's a little bit of uncertainty there.

520
00:57:00,667 --> 00:57:05,027
[SPEAKER_09]: But if you add 2.5% for 2024, when we probably get this thing running, you're looking at about $650,000 to fully fund the program.

521
00:57:05,087 --> 00:57:05,487
[SPEAKER_09]: One other point.

522
00:57:16,014 --> 00:57:24,478
[SPEAKER_09]: If you look through all the documentation, in order to actually administer this program, you need a registered leave administrator.

523
00:57:24,938 --> 00:57:36,763
[SPEAKER_09]: So there's probably going to have to be another position in human resources just to make sure that all the contributions are being reported correctly.

524
00:57:37,623 --> 00:57:44,726
[SPEAKER_09]: And also, if anybody takes advantage of this act, that all the paperwork is filed

525
00:57:45,322 --> 00:57:47,904
[SPEAKER_09]: correctly and in a timely manner.

526
00:57:49,345 --> 00:57:56,490
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's roughly what we'd be looking at if the council votes to fully fund this.

527
00:57:58,131 --> 00:58:02,474
[SPEAKER_09]: In any event, we would need some sort of administrator to make the program work.

528
00:58:03,835 --> 00:58:06,317
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm not sure that HR can take that on right now.

529
00:58:06,977 --> 00:58:07,217
[SPEAKER_09]: Sure.

530
00:58:08,138 --> 00:58:08,438
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

531
00:58:08,458 --> 00:58:09,059
[SPEAKER_11]: Vice President Behrs?

532
00:58:09,868 --> 00:58:11,269
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Madam President.

533
00:58:11,369 --> 00:58:12,029
[SPEAKER_08]: This is helpful.

534
00:58:12,149 --> 00:58:26,355
[SPEAKER_08]: So essentially the range we're talking about if the city were to enact it and then fund the minimum, the city would be paying about $315,475.80 plus the potential either partial or full-time cost of some sort of leave administrator.

535
00:58:28,535 --> 00:58:35,361
[SPEAKER_08]: And then the maximum would be, and again, obviously it would go up in following years as everything does, would be about 637,000.

536
00:58:36,041 --> 00:58:44,868
[SPEAKER_08]: And that would cover, that would mean that employees pay no extra, there'd be no deduction from employee paychecks if we did the 637.

537
00:58:44,908 --> 00:58:51,574
[SPEAKER_08]: I noticed you had out here kind of a little bit of a draft, what an individual employee may pay.

538
00:58:51,594 --> 00:58:56,138
[SPEAKER_08]: You know, I mean, obviously this is someone whose weekly earnings are 1200 per week.

539
00:58:58,317 --> 00:59:01,318
[SPEAKER_09]: So yeah, at $30, that's a quick one.

540
00:59:01,378 --> 00:59:04,119
[SPEAKER_09]: At $30 an hour, they'd make $1,200 a week.

541
00:59:04,659 --> 00:59:08,260
[SPEAKER_09]: The family deduction portion would be $1.32, and medical would be $2.50.

542
00:59:08,320 --> 00:59:14,642
[SPEAKER_09]: So it's $4 a week per employer, about $200 a year for somebody.

543
00:59:14,782 --> 00:59:19,124
[SPEAKER_09]: And $30 is probably on the low end of what we pay everybody.

544
00:59:19,584 --> 00:59:22,585
[SPEAKER_09]: Another consideration on these numbers is that

545
00:59:23,548 --> 00:59:30,489
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm not sure how many employees it would actually work out to, but there's a cap, which is the social security cap, which is what, $120,000.

546
00:59:30,529 --> 00:59:40,151
[SPEAKER_09]: So if you make over that, there aren't that many people who make over that working for the city, but there are a few.

547
00:59:42,372 --> 00:59:47,673
[SPEAKER_09]: Then it's capped at that, so the percentages only apply up to that point.

548
00:59:47,933 --> 00:59:48,193
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

549
00:59:49,850 --> 00:59:52,772
[SPEAKER_08]: but you know, so for 1200 a week, we're talking four bucks a week.

550
00:59:53,233 --> 00:59:54,394
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, and it's linear, right?

551
00:59:54,414 --> 00:59:56,876
[SPEAKER_08]: So if we're talking 2,400, we could be eight bucks a week.

552
00:59:57,056 --> 00:59:57,236
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

553
00:59:57,576 --> 00:59:59,718
[SPEAKER_08]: And that's if the city was putting in its minimum.

554
01:00:00,318 --> 01:00:00,519
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

555
01:00:00,939 --> 01:00:01,239
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

556
01:00:01,339 --> 01:00:13,109
[SPEAKER_08]: So, you know, again, I mean, obviously have the discussion, but that's, um, and again, I think the thing we haven't actually voiced here is what the benefit is, which is, I believe it's, uh, and correct me if I'm wrong, but, um,

557
01:00:13,986 --> 01:00:32,329
[SPEAKER_08]: up to 12 weeks of personal medical leave if you're at 80% of your pay, I believe, and up to 20 and 26 weeks in certain cases of family leave to not just parental leave, but to help out

558
01:00:34,046 --> 01:00:38,452
[SPEAKER_08]: if you need to be caring for a sick parent, you know, sick child.

559
01:00:39,193 --> 01:00:46,584
[SPEAKER_08]: So you have, you know, it's really to address a broad range of needs for people of all ages.

560
01:00:46,644 --> 01:00:48,547
[SPEAKER_08]: I think one thing we know a lot about right now

561
01:00:49,560 --> 01:00:55,743
[SPEAKER_08]: is there's kind of a whole generation of people who have kids that they're taking care of and older parents that they're taking care of.

562
01:00:56,304 --> 01:00:59,085
[SPEAKER_08]: And this does give an option for folks there.

563
01:00:59,125 --> 01:01:07,290
[SPEAKER_08]: So we're not just talking about parental leave, we're talking about a really broad range of benefits for yourself, for your family and different family members.

564
01:01:07,370 --> 01:01:13,813
[SPEAKER_08]: And I think we know all of us have probably experienced in our lives, someone in our family needing that kind of care at some point.

565
01:01:13,993 --> 01:01:16,835
[SPEAKER_08]: And the really difficult decisions that folks have to make

566
01:01:17,856 --> 01:01:25,761
[SPEAKER_08]: to leave a job because they need to care for a parent for half a year, and then they can't get the sick leave or the other kinds of leave or take unpaid leave.

567
01:01:27,442 --> 01:01:33,786
[SPEAKER_08]: So I just want to put out there that, you know, we've been talking about the technicalities of it, but the real material benefit would be huge for a lot of folks.

568
01:01:34,006 --> 01:01:36,728
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, that's a reason that the program was passed into law.

569
01:01:37,989 --> 01:01:41,090
[SPEAKER_08]: One question I have, and these calculations are great.

570
01:01:41,811 --> 01:01:44,853
[SPEAKER_08]: Right now, we have certain programs in the city

571
01:01:45,632 --> 01:01:52,095
[SPEAKER_08]: You know, or at least people are using existing leave programs for similar purposes that this program could be used for.

572
01:01:53,235 --> 01:02:03,060
[SPEAKER_08]: Is it possible to potentially assess, like how much we may be paying right now for someone to use a sick leave bank or something like that or.

573
01:02:04,201 --> 01:02:17,431
[SPEAKER_08]: take leave under existing personnel policy versus what it may, you know, maybe those costs, you know, that may actually, you know, essentially what I'm saying is there may be a cost the city is bearing right now for similar benefits.

574
01:02:19,467 --> 01:02:25,488
[SPEAKER_08]: would it be, is it possible to calculate, you know, maybe what the difference would be if we've moved to this system versus what we're doing now.

575
01:02:25,568 --> 01:02:31,830
[SPEAKER_08]: And if there could be some existing costs that we're already bearing, that would be shifted over into this benefit.

576
01:02:32,010 --> 01:02:36,090
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, that may actually reduce the top line impact on the overall budget.

577
01:02:37,771 --> 01:02:40,491
[SPEAKER_09]: Um, I absolutely see, I see what you're saying.

578
01:02:40,791 --> 01:02:46,213
[SPEAKER_09]: Um, I'd have to talk to HR and I think that would vary based on the individual contracts.

579
01:02:46,513 --> 01:02:46,593
[SPEAKER_02]: Um,

580
01:02:49,573 --> 01:02:58,140
[SPEAKER_09]: exactly what, and I don't know, not being an expert on this program, exactly what it covers.

581
01:02:58,180 --> 01:03:04,386
[SPEAKER_09]: Does it cover after, does it kick in after somebody uses up their sick leave?

582
01:03:06,187 --> 01:03:11,051
[SPEAKER_09]: If Medford has a sick leave bank, we could find out how much that is actually,

583
01:03:18,828 --> 01:03:24,390
[SPEAKER_09]: utilized with working with the HR department.

584
01:03:24,831 --> 01:03:27,292
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't know how easy or hard that would be, frankly.

585
01:03:28,872 --> 01:03:30,373
[SPEAKER_09]: But I definitely see your point.

586
01:03:30,613 --> 01:03:35,555
[SPEAKER_09]: If it replaces something else, we could use that number to know.

587
01:03:35,855 --> 01:03:40,257
[SPEAKER_08]: As I was articulating it, I realized it was complicated enough for me to explain and be complicated enough to calculate.

588
01:03:41,818 --> 01:03:42,618
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll make a stab at it.

589
01:03:43,078 --> 01:03:43,579
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

590
01:03:43,639 --> 01:03:45,680
[SPEAKER_08]: And even something overall, because I think that would just say,

591
01:03:47,311 --> 01:03:50,774
[SPEAKER_08]: we are spending $200,000 a year right now on similar services.

592
01:03:50,854 --> 01:03:51,374
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know.

593
01:03:51,394 --> 01:03:57,318
[SPEAKER_08]: That would be a complete pulled out of the hat number I just raised.

594
01:03:58,959 --> 01:04:04,603
[SPEAKER_08]: That would mean moving to the system may have a different impact overall.

595
01:04:06,965 --> 01:04:11,148
[SPEAKER_08]: One thing I will hold off on that for other questions.

596
01:04:19,090 --> 01:04:20,510
[SPEAKER_11]: If I could just, I'll just interject.

597
01:04:20,551 --> 01:04:21,771
[SPEAKER_11]: It's not a question, just a statement.

598
01:04:21,791 --> 01:04:25,572
[SPEAKER_11]: I know the council has expressed their interest and support of this in the past.

599
01:04:25,632 --> 01:04:37,997
[SPEAKER_11]: And I just, as someone who within the last 10 months, because I'm at a private employer was entitled to 20 weeks leave to heal myself and take care of my newborn son.

600
01:04:39,917 --> 01:04:41,858
[SPEAKER_11]: It's so important.

601
01:04:41,998 --> 01:04:42,978
[SPEAKER_11]: It's still not enough time.

602
01:04:42,998 --> 01:04:47,300
[SPEAKER_11]: It's still nowhere near enough time in a country that has a childcare crisis,

603
01:04:48,657 --> 01:04:54,658
[SPEAKER_11]: high maternal death rates, but it's so much, and it's so much more than our city employees are getting right now.

604
01:04:54,778 --> 01:04:59,719
[SPEAKER_11]: And I just think that if there is any way we can do this, we absolutely owe it to people to do this.

605
01:04:59,739 --> 01:05:07,461
[SPEAKER_11]: And again, understanding it's not just people giving birth, it's people with family medical issues, medical issues, and it's at our fingertips.

606
01:05:07,581 --> 01:05:09,561
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think we owe it to the employees to do it.

607
01:05:09,581 --> 01:05:16,563
[SPEAKER_11]: And I've, you know, again, I've only heard from a handful of folks, but people, those folks, it would change their lives.

608
01:05:17,732 --> 01:05:18,313
[SPEAKER_11]: Absolutely.

609
01:05:18,393 --> 01:05:22,876
[SPEAKER_11]: So just an impassioned plea that if we can get this done, we absolutely do.

610
01:05:26,218 --> 01:05:27,099
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

611
01:05:27,159 --> 01:05:28,460
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a very good opinion.

612
01:05:28,480 --> 01:05:37,166
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, my wife has this, you know, with her job, you know, she's used it many times over the years for, you know, certain things.

613
01:05:37,366 --> 01:05:37,566
[SPEAKER_01]: But I

614
01:05:41,082 --> 01:05:43,343
[SPEAKER_01]: I think there's a criteria that goes along with this.

615
01:05:44,204 --> 01:05:49,986
[SPEAKER_01]: I think you said, I think you have to use up all your sick time first before this kicks in.

616
01:05:51,347 --> 01:06:02,773
[SPEAKER_01]: I remember she had some issues when she took it with her job, but if I'm not mistaken, I think this comes in after all your sick time is used up.

617
01:06:03,293 --> 01:06:04,013
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm not mistaken.

618
01:06:04,073 --> 01:06:06,715
[SPEAKER_01]: I could be wrong on that, but I know there was a criteria.

619
01:06:07,974 --> 01:06:31,401
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, mine's a little different, because I think employers can... Maybe it goes by company or something, but the criteria might have to be decided by the city or whoever's gonna... Yeah, that would be... But it is an important tool, especially for people that have older parents, they need to take care of their parents, things like that, or their husbands or children.

620
01:06:32,782 --> 01:06:36,343
[SPEAKER_01]: It is a valuable tool to have for working people.

621
01:06:36,893 --> 01:06:38,314
[SPEAKER_01]: How the law, excuse me.

622
01:06:39,074 --> 01:06:39,615
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, I was gonna.

623
01:06:39,635 --> 01:06:40,595
[SPEAKER_08]: Oh, if you want to.

624
01:06:40,635 --> 01:06:42,477
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, yeah, I'm sure I know you fought for this.

625
01:06:42,597 --> 01:06:52,943
[SPEAKER_11]: But personal, it's my understanding that private employers could either adopt opt into the state program exactly as it's written, or develop a comparable program.

626
01:06:53,483 --> 01:06:58,446
[SPEAKER_11]: So me personally, I did not have to use sick time, exhaust my sick time before I was able to use the program.

627
01:06:58,747 --> 01:07:00,668
[SPEAKER_11]: But that's how my private employer decided that.

628
01:07:01,204 --> 01:07:01,384
[SPEAKER_08]: Right.

629
01:07:01,424 --> 01:07:21,853
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, yeah, and then that's some that's basically how it works the, you know, employers over a certain size that are not municipal municipalities, which is why we're having the whole discussion, have to provide the coverage, they can either opt into the state system, and the many benefits of that system or offer offer comparable or superior plan for the paid leave.

630
01:07:22,885 --> 01:07:25,206
[SPEAKER_08]: But with the state system, I'd have to double check.

631
01:07:25,286 --> 01:07:27,168
[SPEAKER_08]: I believe it's just a one week waiting period.

632
01:07:27,748 --> 01:07:33,892
[SPEAKER_08]: So it's not the full exhaustion of all of your leave time prior to being eligible for this program.

633
01:07:33,932 --> 01:07:36,994
[SPEAKER_08]: I think it's just a single, you would essentially apply for this program.

634
01:07:37,594 --> 01:07:43,057
[SPEAKER_08]: You could use a week of leave or maybe even take a week of FMLA unpaid, and then you would be eligible for this.

635
01:07:43,538 --> 01:07:47,400
[SPEAKER_08]: Again, it was four years ago now when we were looking at the details of the law.

636
01:07:48,761 --> 01:07:49,001
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

637
01:07:49,963 --> 01:07:54,707
[SPEAKER_08]: But if we were to opt into the state system, those criteria would be determined by the state system itself.

638
01:07:54,747 --> 01:07:57,730
[SPEAKER_08]: And I believe they're the same for everyone who's a part of the state system.

639
01:08:01,494 --> 01:08:03,355
[SPEAKER_11]: Any other questions from the council at this point?

640
01:08:03,496 --> 01:08:04,677
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, I think this is...

641
01:08:05,218 --> 01:08:09,741
[SPEAKER_11]: just due to the complicated nature of this and the fact that no other municipality has done this just yet.

642
01:08:10,161 --> 01:08:18,968
[SPEAKER_11]: We, you know, we obviously have a few more meetings ahead of us to try to figure this out again with union leaders, getting counseling here as well.

643
01:08:19,788 --> 01:08:21,469
[SPEAKER_11]: Councilor Segg.

644
01:08:21,529 --> 01:08:27,734
[SPEAKER_06]: Don't quote me, but I do have the Mass General Law open and it does say seven day wait period.

645
01:08:27,834 --> 01:08:28,394
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, okay.

646
01:08:29,015 --> 01:08:29,575
[SPEAKER_06]: Still got it.

647
01:08:30,236 --> 01:08:30,676
[SPEAKER_06]: Still got it.

648
01:08:33,268 --> 01:08:39,872
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, I'm not legal advice, but I'm reading through it, and I haven't seen anything that goes contrary to that.

649
01:08:40,032 --> 01:08:41,672
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

650
01:08:41,692 --> 01:08:43,633
[SPEAKER_11]: Is there any further discussion at this time?

651
01:08:43,814 --> 01:08:44,634
[SPEAKER_11]: Councilor Collins.

652
01:08:45,314 --> 01:08:46,155
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, President Morrell.

653
01:08:46,235 --> 01:08:48,736
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much, Bob, for being here, providing this context.

654
01:08:49,737 --> 01:08:51,097
[SPEAKER_05]: Love to have a spreadsheet in front of me.

655
01:08:53,459 --> 01:09:00,062
[SPEAKER_05]: No further questions that haven't already been addressed, but just while we're discussing this, and of course, there are many more discussions,

656
01:09:01,302 --> 01:09:11,327
[SPEAKER_05]: On this topic, I just, again, want to reiterate, as other councilors have, I think that there's just so many reasons for us to consider this, for us to take it very seriously, to see how we can make this work for the city.

657
01:09:11,347 --> 01:09:18,771
[SPEAKER_05]: President Murrell spoke eloquently to the sort of humanitarian reasons to have such policy.

658
01:09:20,151 --> 01:09:25,274
[SPEAKER_05]: This is something that employees of all stripes should be entitled to, should be able to benefit from.

659
01:09:26,733 --> 01:09:30,616
[SPEAKER_05]: For a variety of circumstances, this is something that could touch every type of city employee.

660
01:09:31,637 --> 01:09:38,562
[SPEAKER_05]: In addition, we talk a lot about, you know, difficulty in staffing the vacant positions in the City Hall.

661
01:09:39,162 --> 01:09:40,423
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to be able to compete with

662
01:09:41,713 --> 01:09:48,337
[SPEAKER_05]: private sector, you know, that's not the reason I am most excited about us enacting a paid family medical leave ordinance.

663
01:09:48,957 --> 01:09:56,401
[SPEAKER_05]: It's so that people can have a, you know, a benefit that they that they really deserve to, you know, have a comfortable and safe and well rounded life outside of work.

664
01:09:57,461 --> 01:10:09,227
[SPEAKER_05]: But that is also very important for the thriving of the city hall is being able to attract talent to this building and be able to offer compensation benefits on par with private employers.

665
01:10:09,947 --> 01:10:10,748
[SPEAKER_05]: So I look forward to

666
01:10:11,703 --> 01:10:12,944
[SPEAKER_05]: I think we have a lot of work to do.

667
01:10:12,984 --> 01:10:14,686
[SPEAKER_05]: I think we have a lot of work to do.

668
01:10:30,038 --> 01:10:47,401
[SPEAKER_06]: When I think about issues like this, I think about my own parents' lives growing up, raising me, having to take pay cuts to go travel back to Asia, take care of their family, to have me, to give birth to me.

669
01:10:48,041 --> 01:10:58,043
[SPEAKER_06]: And it reminds me that there's still so much more work that we can do in this country to make lives better for working people.

670
01:10:58,362 --> 01:10:59,007
[SPEAKER_06]: working folks.

671
01:11:00,887 --> 01:11:11,171
[SPEAKER_06]: There's, I think one of our counselors loves to remind us to walk the walk in addition to talking the talk.

672
01:11:11,351 --> 01:11:16,493
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think this is one of those examples where we can really take action and walk the walk.

673
01:11:17,574 --> 01:11:23,116
[SPEAKER_06]: There's still details to work through and more feedback to solicit.

674
01:11:23,576 --> 01:11:28,798
[SPEAKER_06]: But I think this is a particularly exciting opportunity for us to take.

675
01:11:30,603 --> 01:11:37,904
[SPEAKER_06]: and to show that Medford is unique amongst cities and that we are a leader in our community.

676
01:11:39,265 --> 01:11:46,106
[SPEAKER_06]: And when we compete with other cities, when it comes to filling our vacancies in City Hall, this will put us a foot forward.

677
01:11:47,066 --> 01:11:49,867
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not the whole, it's not everything, right?

678
01:11:49,907 --> 01:11:54,808
[SPEAKER_06]: It won't completely solve all our problems, but it positions, puts us in a better position to succeed.

679
01:11:56,589 --> 01:12:02,321
[SPEAKER_06]: And Councillor Collins also alluded to the fact that we are competing with the private sector and I think.

680
01:12:04,165 --> 01:12:12,070
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, there's a crisis, not only in Medford, but nationally, of filling up public sector jobs with talent.

681
01:12:12,310 --> 01:12:23,176
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's something that oftentimes I think governments are hamstringing ourselves a little too much by not providing the benefits that can compete with the private sector.

682
01:12:23,517 --> 01:12:27,559
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think this is one of the situations in which there is a race to the top.

683
01:12:29,415 --> 01:12:36,959
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's, again, you know, it's not the main reason why I'm supporting this, but I think it is a major reason why we should support this.

684
01:12:38,279 --> 01:12:40,200
